Impact of public library resources on K-12 learning outcomes in the state of Kansas - 2019

December 10, 2023

Use the Tidyverse dialect of R for data wrangling:

library(tidyverse)

Sources of original data files:

The poverty rates are in a file that was generated (after specified inputs) and downloaded from Census web site, American Community Survey 5 year estimates (2017-2021), from this site: https://data.census.gov/table?g=040XX00US20&y=2021

Original file name (assigned by Census site) is ACSST5Y2021.S1701_Data.csv. For this and all other files, all manipulations are done with the code in this file. ACS 5y estimates 2021 (so 2017-2021); school districts in Kansas.

Geographic Information files grf19_lea_tract.csv census tracts for school districts, 2019 Actually end up usingsing

2015_2022_ACT_Full.csv ACT scores per school and district, 2015-2022 https://ksreportcard.ksde.org/act_scores.aspx?org_no=State&rptType=

US Dept Edu collects State assessments in Reading/Language Arts and Math. The website for downloading data is here: https://www2.ed.gov/about/inits/ed/edfacts/data-files/index.html

From above, downloaded reading data set at district level for 2018-2019 school year (before pandemic) There is wide and long form. Use wide. rla-achievement-lea-sy2018-19-wide.csv

LEA stands for âschool districtâ = Local Educational Agency

Preparing the Census poverty rates file

# read in data file as tibble object
acs_poverty_ori <- read_csv("ACSST5Y2021.S1701-Data.csv")

Columns to be selected (descriptions are from an Excel file of metadata that was downloaded from Census site along with the data file; this meta data is also present as a second âlabelsâ row in the above file):

âGEO_IDâ is Census id for the row; first row is entire state and other rows are all school districts in Kansas

âNAMEâ is Kansas for first data row; name of school districts for other rows

âS1701_C01_001Eâ is the total population for the GEO_ID (Kansas, and each school district), for whom poverty rate is determined

âS1701_C01_002Eâ is population under 18, for whom poverty rate is determined

âS1701_C03_001Eâ is percent below poverty for total population (KS for first data row, school district for all other rows)

âS1701_C03_002Eâ is percent below poverty for under 18 (KS for first row, school districts for other rows)

# Select column names for potential data to be used from Census data file, to be joined with other data sets. Rename columns to be nicer.
acs_poverty_selects <- acs_poverty_ori |> 
  select(
    GEO_ID,
    NAME,
    S1701_C01_001E,
    S1701_C01_002E,
    S1701_C03_001E,
    S1701_C03_002E
  ) |> 
  rename(
    geo_id = GEO_ID,
    total_pop = S1701_C01_001E,
    under18_pop = S1701_C01_002E,
    total_below_pov = S1701_C03_001E,
    under18_below_pov =S1701_C03_002E
  )

Filter out (remove) âKansasâ row (full state) and metadata row (so, first two rows), leaving only KS school districts as data rows.

acs_poverty_districts_a <- acs_poverty_selects |> 
  filter(
    geo_id != "Geography" & geo_id != "0400000US20"
  )

# head(acs_poverty_districts_a)

Output sample shows all column data types are chr (because they all contained metadata string data type, now removed.) Will need to swap most columns (except district name) to numeric data type.

Remove first part of geo_id number which just indicates type of geo id I think (it is same for all rows). This way it can be joined with files that have abbreviated geo_id code for school district. This requires splitting the geo_id column into two, and keeping only the second one.

acs_poverty_districts_b <- acs_poverty_districts_a |> 
  separate_wider_position(
    cols = geo_id,
    widths = c(toss = 9, geo_id = 7)
  ) |> 
  select(-toss)

Separate school district name from school district number (because test score data has district number column that can be joined, after further manipulationâ¦) and drop the word âKansasâ from district names (after assigning it to a column called âstateâ)

acs_poverty_districts_c <- acs_poverty_districts_b |> 
  separate_wider_delim(
    cols = NAME,
    delim = ",",
    names = c("district", "state")
  ) |> select(-state) |> 
  separate_wider_delim(
    cols = district,
    delim = "District",
    names = c("district_name", "district_number")
  )

# Now district name and district number are split into 2 columns;
# the word "District" is missing because it was used as delimiter.

Change string data types to numeric data types as needed

acs_poverty_districts_d <- acs_poverty_districts_c |> 
  mutate(
    total_pop = as.numeric(total_pop),
    under18_pop = as.numeric(under18_pop),
    total_below_pov = as.numeric(total_below_pov),
    under18_below_pov = as.numeric(under18_below_pov)
    )

Join ACT scores to ACS Census poverty rates using school district number

Do left join with ACS census table on the left. There are four more rows in ACT scores data than ACS poverty; one of these is not a district and should be lost (remember, these are rows that did not have a building number, and thatâs not a perfect way to filter districts from schools). Also, some of what remained in ACT Districts table seem like not quite districts, like âSchool for the Deaf.â Also, KSDE ACT scores data set includes several private religious schools that are missing from Census ACS data set.

The other thing is, Shawnee Mission School District is missing a district number in ACS Census data set, but it is in the KSDE data set. It is number 512. This is an important district, so add its number to the Census data set. I cheated and just added to original data file. It was the only missing number for Kansas and must have been an error.

The join did not work. Probably have space or tab or something in the district number for one of the data sets, so nothing matches for the join. So make them both numeric instead of string:

ACT_2019_district_no <- ACT_2019_district_no |> 
  mutate(district_no = as.numeric(district_no))
acs_poverty_districts_d <- acs_poverty_districts_d |> 
  mutate(district_number = as.numeric(district_number))

Now it works:

acs_poverty_districts_scores <- acs_poverty_districts_d |> 
  left_join(
    ACT_2019_district_no,
    by = c("district_number" = "district_no")
  )

(note that I repeated the above step later when I redid everything with RLA_scores added to ACT scores)

All looks good. Rename District Composite to ACT_Score. Also, district name is in two columns, slightly different format â it is nice because reassuring that the join worked as expected. But I can delete one of them.

acs_poverty_districts_scores <- acs_poverty_districts_scores |> 
  select(-`Organization Name`) |> 
  rename(ACT_Score = `District Composite`)

Correlation of ACT scores with Childhood Poverty

Letâs take a peek at how well percent below poverty for under 18 year-olds correlates with ACT scores

plotACTpoverty <- acs_poverty_districts_scores |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = ACT_Score, y = under18_below_pov)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  theme_bw() +

Looking through the columns of this easier-to-peruse set, we can easily eliminate the following columns because they will not be useful (I deleted from above code):

CENTLIB,BRANLIB,BKMOB (central, branch and bookmobile) because they are either mostly all â1â or â0â = rare and not helpful.

STAFFEXP because lots of libraries did not report how much they spent on compensation (or else it is not in this public file)

CAP_REV and CAPITAL because lots of â0â or high numbers; apparently this refers to putting up new buildings and should not be considered in a single year span (I thought it would be things like electricity and water and furniture and computers, etc but apparently not)

AUDIO_DL and VIDEO_DL = Digital audio and digital video in the librariesâ âcollectionsâ because they are same for most of the libraries; probably subscribe to same service, or Kansas State negotiated deals for the state.

WEBVISIT because too many libraries did not track this or did not provide it.

Split the dashes scores into two columns, make them numeric, then average them

edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_split <- edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash |> 
  separate_wider_delim(
    cols = ALL_RLA00pctprof_1819,
    delim = "-",
    names = c("low", "high")
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    high = as.numeric(high),
    low = as.numeric(low)
  )
RLA_Scores <- (edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_split$low + edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_split$high)/2

edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_ave <- edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_split |> 
  mutate(RLA_Scores = RLA_Scores) |> 
  select(-c("low", "high"))

Now recombine the two parts of the dataset

edfacts_2019_KS_sel_b <- rbind(edfacts_2019_KS_sel_dash_ave, edfacts_2019_KS_sel_NOdash)

Now fix district number so it is a simple number with no prefixes. Need to remove first 5 characters and keep last 3

edfacts_2019_KS_sel <- edfacts_2019_KS_sel_b |>
